5. 🔍 Theoretical Validation & Metrics

Since the thesis is purely mathematical, we establish the validity of our framework through:

1. Proof of Contraction (Theorem 1): Provide a complete, rigorous proof for the coupled $(Z, A)$ system, including explicit bounds on $\kappa_{ZA}, \kappa_{AZ}$ in terms of network parameters. Show necessity of the small-gain condition via counterexamples.
2. Proof of Safety (Theorem 2): Derive the robust CBF condition and prove forward invariance. Discuss feasibility under relative-degree assumptions.
3. Proof of Equivariance (Theorem 3): Provide a detailed proof that the entire pipeline is SE(3)-equivariant, handling the scalar adjacency invariance carefully.
4. Complexity Analysis: Prove $O(N \log N)$ amortized complexity using LSH for attention; or provide a rigorous argument for $O(N)$ under assumptions. We adopt the LSH approach for definiteness.
5. Comparison with Existing Frameworks: Mathematically compare CDIA with:
   · Static GNNs (fixed $A$)
   · Dense transformers ($O(N^2)$)
   · Safe learning frameworks (e.g., [Ames et al., 2019] with CBF, [Taylor et al., 2020] with learning)
   · Equivariant networks (TFN, SE(3)-Transformer) – show that CDIA extends them with dynamic graphs and safety.
6. Limitations and Failure Modes: Dedicate a section (see below) to discuss when assumptions fail, e.g., when $\lambda_2 \to 0$ (graph disconnection), when the small-gain condition is violated (leading to ISS only), when the robust CBF becomes infeasible, etc.

